      <div xml:id="NA271-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu (ET: makaṭ pōkkiya tāy) maṉaimaruṇṭu colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what is said in the confusion of the house.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA271">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            irumpuṉiṟ ṟerumaip peruñcevik kuḻavi</l>
<l>            paintā teruviṉ vaikutuyiṉ maṭiyuñ</l>
<l>            ceḻuntaṇ maṉaiyō ṭemmiva ṇoḻiyac</l>
<l>            celperuṅ kāḷai poymaruṇṭu cēynāṭṭuc</l>
<l>            cuvaikkāy nellip pōkkarum poṅkar </l>
<l>            vīḻkaṭait tiraḷkā yoruṅkuṭaṉ ṟiṉṟu</l>
<l>            vīcuṉaic ciṟunīr kuṭiyiṉaḷ kaḻinta</l>
<l>            kuvaḷai yuṇkaṇeṉ makaḷō raṉṉa</l>
<l>            ceypōḻ veṭṭip peyta lāya          ceypāḻ paṭuppa veytuyirt tayarun</l>
<l>            mālaiviri nilaviṟ peyarpupuṟaṅ kāṇṭaṟku </l>
<l rend="indent4">            tuyarviṉai yāḷaṉiṟ peyarpupuṟaṅ</l>
<l>            māyirun tāḻi kavippat</l>
<l>            tāviṉṟu kaḻikaveṟ koḷḷāk kūṟṟē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>May Yama, who didn’t take me, pass away without strength,</l>
<l rend="indent3">to be buried in a big large pot<note place="foot">T.V.G. sees here a real allusion to burial in pots; cf. the parallel in PN 238.</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent2">for [my] seeing the backs, moving in the moonlight spreading at evening,</l>
<l rend="indent2">of the [girl] companions<note place="foot">T.V.G. reads here a complicated story of the backs belonging to the eloped couple that has been brought up, but I rather think that the group of girls wears the palmyra for decoration which reminds the mother by its tenderness and freshness of her eloped daughter - this allows us to stay within the limits of the usual syntax, and it makes as much sense.</note> cutting [and] wearing red(?)<note place="foot">Do we have to read cey as the verbal root here, meaning specially prepared palmyra leaves, or is this the rarer adjective belonging to cemmai "redness", referring to the freshness of the leaf?</note> palmyra leaves,</l>
<l rend="indent">just as my daughter with collyrium eyes [as] blue waterlilies, who is gone</l>
<l rend="indent">– one who drank<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kuṭiyiṉaḷ</term> can either be read as a <term xml:lang="ta">muṟṟeccam</term> governed by <term xml:lang="ta">kaḻinta</term> or else as the predicate of an independent sentence.</note> the little water from the subsiding mountain spring,</l>
<l rend="indent">having eaten together the globular unripe fruits within the area of falling</l>
<l rend="indent2">in the grove difficult to approach, from the Nelli with tasty unripe fruits,</l>
<l rend="indent2">a distant land, bewitched by the lies of the [fast-?]going big young man,</l>
<l rend="indent">so that we<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">em</term>: actually we do not need an oblique here, but a nominative, as subject to <term xml:lang="ta">oḻiya</term>.</note> stay behind here with the prosperous cool house,</l>
<l rend="indent2">where the large-eared calf of the buffalo, newly born [and] dark,</l>
<l rend="indent2">drowses into sleep, being kept in the dung [spread] with fresh pollen.</l>
    </lg>
      </div>
